Case Project 2-1
Week 2, 4 September, 2025
Testing Password Strength
Prompt:
How strong are your passwords? Various online tools can provide information on password
strength, but not all feedback is the same. First, assign the numbers 1–3 to three passwords that
are very similar (but not identical) to passwords you are currently using, and write down the
number (not the password) on a piece of paper. Then, enter those passwords into these three
online password testing services:
● How Secure Is My Password (www.security.org/how-secure-is-my-password/)
● Password Checker Online (http://password-checker.online-domain-tools.com/)
● The Password Meter (www.passwordmeter.com/)
Next to each number, record the strength of that password as indicated by these three online
tools. Then use each online password tester to modify the password by adding more random
numbers or letters to increase its strength. How secure are your passwords? Would any of these
tools encourage someone to create a stronger password? Which provided the best information?
Create a one-paragraph summary of your findings.
security.org/how-secure-is-my-password, 3 hundred billion years
password-checker.online-domain-tools.com, (gpu) 5 quadrillion year
passwordmeter.com, didn't give a time estimate for cracking, but gave great analysis
Security.org gave the least information on why or how a password was secure.
Password-checker gave a better analysis on what was used and why it was secure.
Passwordmeter.com gave the best analsys out of all these sites and did a nice job of helping to visualize
how to create a very strong password using it’s data table.
It turns out my passwords are sufficiently secure. Passwordmeter.com would definetly help someone
understand what would make a password stronger. You can sculpt your password in real time and get
feedback needed to make an ultra-secure password or at least follow their idea of good practices.
I had no idea that having two characters next to each other that share the same case is considered bad
practice.
